Events in '''LGBT history in Norway''' include:

The penal code's paragraph 213 was the order for the punishment (''straffebud'') of homosexual men. In June 1968 [[Elisabeth Schweigaard Selmer|then minister of justice]] said that "it is not stated, if the paragraph should be lifted [or removed]". A different government came to power in 1969.<ref name=Fib>[http://www.aftenposten.no/meninger/kronikker/Blabla-homovennlighet-er-en-blabla-skrone-7633508.html#.U8ZOLJSSyVO Blåblå homovennlighet er en blåblå skrøne] [Blue-Blue gay-friendliness is a blue-blue fib]</ref>

In 1970, a question was registered for [[interpellation (politics)|interpellation]] in Parliament, by representative [[Arne Kielland]]. The Borten Government had no intent to answer the interpellation, but forwarded a law proposal about, [[age of sexual consent]] for gay males—18 years; the age limit for all other—16 years. (A different government came to power in March 1971.<ref name=Fib />

[[Homosexuality]] in [[Norway]] was decriminalised in 1972.<ref name="History">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-25927595 |title=Where is it illegal to be gay? |accessdate=13 February 2014 |work=BBC News}}</ref>

In 1979 [[Wenche Lowzow]], MP [[came out of the closet]].<ref name=Fib />
