The '''Macedonian National Movement''' (abbreviated '''MANAPO''') ({{lang-mk|Македонски Национален Покрет}},<ref>The modern [[Macedonian language|Macedonian]] word for "movement" is ''движење'', but before the language was codified some Macedonians used the [[Serbian language|Serbian]] word ''покрет'', due to the subjection under Serbian educational system</ref> [[Transliteration of Macedonian|transliterated]]: ''Makedonski Nacionalen Pokret'') was a [[leftist]] movement started in 1936 among the progressive [[ethnic Macedonians|Macedonian]] students in the [[Belgrade]] and [[Zagreb]] universities in  the period between the [[World Wars]]. 

MANAPO's aims were to help bring about democracy in Yugoslavia and to fight for the right to self-determination of the Bulgarians in [[Vardar Macedonia]].<ref>http://znam.bg/com/action/showArticle?encID=2&article=3131621987&sectionID=1&sq=%D0%BC%D0%B0%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%B4%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%8F</ref> The official historiography in [[Communist Yugoslavia|post-1945 Yugoslavia]] and present-day [[Republic of Macedonia]] plays down the Bulgarian nature of this organization and claims that MANAPO's platform was based on the awaking of the Macedonian national conscience among the Macedonian Slavic-speaking population, the affirmation of the [[Macedonian language]] as well as fight against the [[Serbs|Serbian]] hegemony and [[fascism]].<ref>[http://www.veles.gov.mk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=28&Itemid=52&limit=1&limitstart=3 Балканските војни и I светска војна - Општина Велес] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719093828/http://www.veles.gov.mk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=28&Itemid=52&limit=1&limitstart=3 |date=2011-07-19 }}</ref>

When MANAPO was dissolved in the beginning of the [[Second World War]], with some of its members entering the ranks of the [[Communist Party of Yugoslavia]], while others felt the aims of the organization had been established with the "[[Occupation of Yugoslav Macedonia during World War II|liberation]]" of Vardar Macedonia by Bulgaria in 1941.<ref>[http://www.novamakedonija.com.mk/star/DesktopDefault.aspx?tabindex=6&tabid=1&EditionID=130&ArticleID=4717 ''Втората светска војна зеде околу 65 милиони жртви''. "НОВА МАКЕДОНИЈА"]{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

