'''Marc Gopin''', scholar and practitioner, is the director of the [[Center for World Religions, Diplomacy and Conflict Resolution|Center for World Religions, Diplomacy and Conflict Resolution (CRDC)]], and  James H. Laue Professor at the School of Conflict Analysis and Resolution at [[George Mason University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://crdc.gmu.edu/staff/marc-gopins-bio/|title=Marc Gopin - Center for World Religions, Diplomacy, and Conflict ResolutionCenter for World Religions, Diplomacy, and Conflict Resolution|last=|first=|date=|website=crdc.gmu.edu|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-02-02}}</ref> Arlington, Virginia, USA. The Association of Conflict Resolution<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.acrannualconference.org/acr-leadership.html|title=Association for Conflict Resolution Leadership|last=|first=|date=|website=My Site|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-02-01}}</ref> recently awarded Gopin The Peacemaker Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.acrannualconference.org/2016-award-recipients.html|title=2016 Award Recipients|website=www.acrannualconference.org|access-date=2017-02-12}}</ref> for his contribution to the Conflict Resolution Field. Note that, in 2008 he also received the Andrew Thomas Peacebuilder Award from the New York State Dispute Resolution Association<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nysdra.org/page/AwardNominations/Awards.htm|title=Awards - New York State Dispute Resolution Association, Inc.|last=|first=|date=|website=www.nysdra.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-02-04}}</ref> (NYSDRA). Gopin has pioneered peacebuilding projects at CRDC and trained thousands of peacebuilders in Afghanistan, Iran, Syria, Palestine and Israel on strategies to address complex conflicts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scar.gmu.edu/people/marc-gopin|title=Marc Gopin {{!}} The School for Conflict Analysis and Resolution|website=scar.gmu.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-02-12}}</ref> He studies dilemmas of values in global conflicts and diverse contexts where [[religion]] and [[culture]] play a crucial role in [[Group conflict|conflicts]] and [[conflict resolution]].

Gopin's particular emphasis is on the role of religion and culture in not only key to conflict, but is critical to reaching lasting resolution between peoples and nations. Widely recognized for his lectures and training on peacemaking strategies, Gopin has worked in Ireland, Israel, India, Switzerland, and Italy, and has presented at Harvard, Yale, Columbia, and Princeton Universities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pa.cair.com/files/Changing_Course.pdf|title=Changing Course: a new Direction for U.S. Relations With the Muslim World|last=|first=|date=|website=U.S. Muslim Engagement Project|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> He has also engaged in back channel diplomacy with religious, political, and military figures on both sides of entrenched conflicts, especially in the [[Israeli–Palestinian conflict|Israel-Palestine]] conflict, Jordan, and Syria<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scar.gmu.edu/people/marc-gopin|title=Marc Gopin {{!}} The School for Conflict Analysis and Resolution|last=|first=|date=|website=scar.gmu.edu|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-02-02}}</ref>

==Education==
Gopin got his B.A. in European Intellectual History from Columbia College in 1979. In 1983, Gopin was ordained as a rabbi at [[Yeshiva University]], where he was a student of Rabbi [[Joseph Soloveitchik]]. Though ordained as an Orthodox rabbi, he eventually stopped identifying with any Jewish denomination.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Lonely Man of Peace|url=http://www.jpost.com/Magazine/Features/Article.aspx?id=166295| publisher=The Jerusalem Post|date=January 21, 2010|author= Lauren Gelfond Feldinger}}</ref>  He received his M.A. from [[Brandeis University]] in 1988 where he also got his PhD in 1992 from the Department of Near Eastern and Judaic Studies. His dissertation Topic: The Religious Ethics of [[Samuel David Luzzatto]].

